				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">For instance, Carter had that nightmare of a hostage situation, Reagen came to office and *bam* the hostages were released.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Carter's problem was that he had no precedent for such an event like 60 American citizens being taken hostage over seas and lack of a definitive plan to follow.  The man looked like he had finished crying when he made the announcement about the embassy in Tehran, that combined with the economy / gas crisis cost him the election in 80.  I don't know if Reagan can be truly credited with the release of the hostages, he hadn't even been in a day when they were released.  Then of course later he gave us the Contra scandal that flew in the face of his foreign policy.
<br />

<br />
The largest factor that kept terrorism out of American soil was and still is for the most part, distance.  Getting from Saudi Arabia or Syria to the United States is not an easy endeavor.  Once that distance is taken away the probability for attacks becomes greater, ie Iraq.  Terrorists simply cross a border or two rather than an ocean.<span class="gensmall"></span>


