				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody">Perhaps you are trying to ask (with my opinions at the end):
<br />
Is Islamic terrorism going to get better, worse or stay the same (as a result of the invasion of Iraq)? 
<br />
Is Domestic terrorism going to get better, worse or stay the same (as a result of the invasion of Iraq)? 
<br />
Did/does the invasion of Iraq motivate or deter Islamic terrorists?
<br />
Will the presence or absence of bush make a difference in Islamic terrorism?
<br />
Will the presence or absence of bush make a difference in Domestic terrorism?
<br />
What motivates Islamic terrorists?
<br />
What motivates Domestic terrorists?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Will terrorism Increase because the terrorists are no longer afraid of their countries being invaded?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">Nope. Very few Islamic terrorist organizations are getting governmental support. And the Saudis (our alleged allies in the region) are the only ones spending big bucks supporting terrorist organizations. <span style="font-style: italic">Crusader</span> is a very emotionally charged word in the Arab world. A US president that comes across as a crusader will automatically be feared and opposed by Arabs. Feared in the way that everything such a person does will be considered suspect, like everything a rabid dog licks. A lot stronger distrust than merely BushLied(tm). And not a fear that you could pretend is <span style="font-style: italic">a good thing</span>. Maybe the Arabs have some tinfoil hat and black helicopter grade distrust, but just as unconvincible by any evidence. I predict that invading anyother Islamic country in the near future will provoke a permanent and irrevocable war with Islam. The kind you can only end with nuking everyone from Morocco to Indonesia, killing billions, to avoid losing. Whether there is a good excuse or not won't disuade the tinfoil turban crowd. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Is Islamic terrorism going to get better, worse or stay the same?</span>If bush and binladen have succeeded in making/defining the <span style="font-style: italic">war against terror</span> to be the <span style="font-style: italic">war against islam</span>, then it will never ever get better until either the USA or Islam has been utterly destroyed. Palestinian terrorism against Israel is the model to understand here: it will end when the Palestinians or Israelis are all dead. The rebels in Iraq are trying to transform from the remnants of Hussein's regime (and their sympathisers) into guerillas trying to expell foreign invaders. It does not help that some of the folks on the "ruling council" have engaged in terrorist acts themselves. It also does not help that the council gives the appearance of religious favoritism. Historically, that transformation sometimes works, and when it does not, the group ends up becoming bandits (an example of a failed transformation would be the IRA, they currently rob banks, extort money from businesses, import and sell drugs to support their activities). An example of a successful transformation was the Taliban in Afghanistan.
<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Is Domestic terrorism going to get better, worse or stay the same?</span>
<br />
Domestic terrorism is the big blind spot of folks in the USA. Domestic terrorist groups that manufacture Sarin and Cyanide bombs get ignored by the media. If it had been found in Iraq, instead of Texas and Washington, everyone would agree that invading Iraq was justified, instead gets ignored since no one seems to want to talk about Domestic terrorism. <a href="http://www.thememoryhole.org/terror/tyler-terror.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">sample</a>. I am not sure if Puerto Rican separatists are still committing terrorist acts (like shooting people in congress).  
