				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody">Actually Carter did have precedent and Americans had been taken hostage prior to Iran and held captive.  I will be the first to say that Jimmy Carter is a good and decent man.  He has deep moral and religious convictions that lead him to think that violence is never the answer.  That didn't make him bad, but it did make him ineffective in dealing with that situation.  He hamstrung the size and composition of the military rescue operation against his military advisors wishes.  Other good men died because of this lack of support.
<br />

<br />
Reagan openly stated on the campaign trail that the hostage situation would end one way or another with him assuming office.  He made no bones about the fact that his solution (having seen all diplomatic efforts fail already) was massive and focused military power.   Reagan gets elected, the terrorists are rushing around feeding them and trying to make them ready to get home before the bombs fall.  The Libyans are proven to sponsor terrorists, np Reagan sends in the F-111's to show them that we feel thats not a good decision.  Now around every 5 years, good ol Qadaffi comes out and shakes his fist on TV, says America is bad, and hauls balls back to his bunkers.
<br />

<br />
I am not saying America, or its Presidents are always right.  We can and do make some bad decisions.  As human beings though, any decision to show force to people who can only understand force is usually a good decision.
<br />

<br />
Typically the bullies in the world have the same mentality as school yard bullies.  Did the school yard bullies stop because they got in trouble?  No, it took someone kicking their butt to straighten them out.
<br />

<br />
When you look at the "terrorist states" in the world (i.e. those willing to use terrorism as an internal and/or external political tool), you see the same mentality.  Its sort of a "we know you won't do anything about it, so this is the level we will conduct relations with you" attitude.  
<br />

<br />
Having never lived in a terrorist state, I do not have first hand information on life their.  However, I do have second hand info.  My neighbors when I was a teen had escaped the persecutions of the Ayatollah (sp?).  They were nice, quiet, God (in this case Allah) fearing people; who lead simple lives.  They worked their butts off and there was always a stream of new relatives showing up to help out and get set up before moving on.  To be honest, at first I was suspicious as hell of them.  However one day I got a paniced phone call from them to come over right away.  It turns out our 40lb dog had managed to get through the fence and was "staring at them" through their living room window.  The entire family was standing or huddled on top of the tallest pieces of furniture and the women were all crying.  I found it kind of bizarre, but took the dog home and figured out how the dog got through.  I went over later to appologize that our harmless, friendly dog had come over and scared them.  This is when I got a shock, these people were terrified of all dogs.  It seems the Ayatollah had "death squads" with man eating dogs that would literally tear people apart in the streets or their homes for imagined infractions.
<br />

<br />
Over the years, I found this family to be some of the best American citizens I have ever met.  They celebrated American holidays with a fervor while still maintaing their distinct Arab culture.  They worked hard and were in support of violence as the first solution against terrorists.  These people scrimped and saved, bought businesses and used their profits to bribe Iranian oifficials to allow more of their friends and relatives to imigrate to America.
<br />

<br />
You want to know what a free and loving paradise Iraq was before the invasion?  Check Amnesty International's web site.  It lists them among the worst in human rights violations.  I believe the number of missing in official custody had topped 100K since Saddam took power there.  I firmly believe that man has reservations in the very lowest levels of Hell.  My wish is that if found guilty by trial, he is turned over to the people who survived his tortures for a long and messy execution.  Heck, I'd buy them some slow burning wood if they want to burn him at the stake.
<br />

<br />
Might does not make right.  However sometimes it is the only tool to use against people who believe it does.  Those who believe Bush is some crazed, blood thirsty president have a differing viewpoint from mine.  I believe he is a good and honest man who agonized over the fact he was sending American men and boys to battle.  He knew some would die, but understood that it was for the greater good of a larger number of people.  He made the right decision, and I stand behind him and his job as the US President.
<br />

<br />
As president he has been working on combating terrorist organizations and states since the day he assumed office.
<br />

<br />
Bush will most certainly have my vote in the coming election.<span class="gensmall"></span>


