				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody">Maybe you are very young, but there are some here who remember:
<br />
1 - The oil embargo in the early 1970s.  
<br />
2 - And the longshoreman strike on the west coast recently. 
<br />
3 - Perhaps you are forgetting the banana wars with the EU (they have a legal standard for what species of banana can be sold in europe, and the banana sold in the US is not one of the approved species). 
<br />
4 - Perhaps you are also forgetting the issue with genetically modified (GM) foods, many people refuse to eat them, and many countries are starting to ban anything from entering that contains ANY GM food products. Those people remember that their governments claimed that mad-cow-disease could not be spread by food, which has been shown to be the only way it spreads. As a result, they don't trust the claims that GM food is safe. The US government is claiming it is safe (and most of it probably is safe), and threatening a trade war if the others don't roll over and surrender. 
<br />

<br />
It has happened in the past, and it can happen again in the future. Failure to remember history can be a very very expensive mistake. International trade is getting more and more interconnected and brittle. It would be easy for a small pissing match over some little thing to blow up and stop the wheels that keep you fed and clothed. Or for some small link in the chain to decide to say "no." Having a bunch of guns won't do you any good when I burn my crops to keep you from getting my property. What? You don't think that can happen? Then you never learned history. And you don't know people.
<br />

<br />
When someone claims the US doesn't need the rest of the world (or vice versa), it shows they don't know beans.<span class="gensmall"></span>


