				<td colspan="2" align="left"><div class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">When someone claims the US doesn't need the rest of the world (or vice versa), it shows they don't know beans. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Unrealistic.  The US props up so many developing countries that if the world at large would suddenly conspire to stop trading with us, a good 80% of it would go into the crapper long before we would.  In fact, we would probably outlast everyone.  We can make enough food in the US to feed ourselves.  We have extensive oil reservers and the possibility of turning Alaska into swiss cheese and sucking it dry, plus offshore platforms in the Gulf of Mexico.  Of course, gas prices, along with many other staples, would shoot through the roof...but it would be nowhere near as bad here as in many of the countries we cut off.  
<br />

<br />
Additionally, our emprical, capitalistic nature has led us to having extensive ownership of property and industry in many countries abroad...so while the country might stop trading it's state gained products with us, we would still have our own companies in those countries to help out...and woe be to the country who tried to start some stuff with US civilians overseas (unless Dean wins, then it'll be safe to do whatever you want to US citizens).
<br />

<br />
And, in the worst case scenario...we can probably take what we need from the rest of the world if it comes down to it.  There is no military threat to the US on this side of the globe.  No single country in the world could take us on head-to-head short of a nuclear strike.  The entire world combined does not have the amphibious assets to stage an attack on the US homeland...not to mention the fact that just about every Joe Civilian in US has a gun...and some of us have lots of guns.
<br />

<br />
Back to the original topic though.  I think that in the short term we will probably see an increase in terrorist activity for another 18-24 months.  However, terrorist leadership is suffering BIG TIME right now (though the media doesn't want you to know that...it's not exciting if we're winning).  Did you maybe see those "High Value Target" playing cards that were released when we went into Iraq?  Well, we've captured or killed about 75% of them...including #'s 1 2 and 3 on the list.  
<br />

<br />
We'll get Osama sooner or later.  Catching Saddam goes to show that it doesn't matter where you hide.  Hole in the ground or cave in the mountains, sooner or later someone is going to sell your %@$# out for 25 million bones.  
<br />

<br />
Most terrorists are uneducated and ill-equipped to do much damage short of blowing themselves up without leadership.  Like an angry mob, all it does is stand around and yell a lot unless a charismatic leader comes along and gives it direction.  Then it becomes a dangerous weapon.  Killing terrorist leadership will not stop the occasional wanker from strapping on a bomb and running into a crowded restaraunt in Isreal, but it will stop them from crashing planes into buildings.  
<br />

<br />
For example, I see lots of interviews with pissed off Iraqi's saying that they're ready to take up Jihad against the US forces.  That's fine, it's easy to talk a good game, but when it comes down to it, when terrorist go head to head with coalition forces...they lose.  And they lose HUGE.  
<br />

<br />
The crippling of terrorist leadership will begin to show in the near future.  It won't ever stop it completly, but (even though the media would say otherwise) most of these cats are not going to pick up a gun or RPG and point it at our forces...because most of them don't want to die.<span class="gensmall"></span>


